\begin_layout Subsection*
(a) 5 points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{g_{i}},i=1...M\}$
\end_inset

 is M.
 Therefore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
dim\left(R(\boldsymbol{G})\right) & \leq & M<N=dim(â„^{N})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
(b) 10 points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\boldsymbol{H_{ij}} & = & \boldsymbol{g_{i}}^{T}\boldsymbol{g_{j}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diagonal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{H}$
\end_inset

 are the squared lengths of the column vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

, the off-diagnoal elements measure how much the column vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 project onto each other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
(c) 5 points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\boldsymbol{G}^{T}\boldsymbol{d} & = & (\boldsymbol{g_{1}}^{T}\boldsymbol{d},...,\boldsymbol{g_{M}}^{T}\boldsymbol{d})^{T}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 into the model space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's continue the discussions in (b).
 Suppose we project a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 into the column space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

, the coordinates are 
\begin_inset Formula $(m_{1},...,m_{M})$
\end_inset

.
 If the length of certain column vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is small, an error in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 will cause a big error in 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The error in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 also tends to affect those 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 similarly if their corresponding column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are near parallel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
(d) 5 points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Gm}$
\end_inset

 equals the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 in the model space.
 Thus, the least-squares solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{m}$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 in the model space.
\end_layout

